  "method": "1) Build the right text and language model first. Retrieve and transform in-domain text using a dataset-retrieval-and-transformation pipeline: mine public corpora, manuals, chat logs, and domain documents that match the target language/domain; then normalize to ASR style (spoken-form punctuation, numeral expansion, abbreviations, code-switch variants) and expand with rare terms and morphology. From this script, construct a pronunciation lexicon or grapheme mapping and train a compact domain language model (e.g., 4–6 gram and a small transformer LM) for shallow fusion or WFST decoding. Deduplicate and stratify the script for coverage over word frequency bins, numerics, entities, and prosody markers.\n\n2) Turn the script into strong synthetic audio with transfer-learned multilingual TTS. Start from a robust multilingual TTS trained on high-resource languages; fine-tune lightly toward the target language or accent using any available transcribed minutes or pseudo-transcripts, leveraging codec-based acoustic tokenization to preserve cross-lingual prosody and phonotactics. Synthesize 100–1000 hours with multiple speakers, speaking rates, and style/noise profiles; augment on-the-fly with room impulse responses, codecs, and gain perturbations. Ensure phoneme and syllable coverage by sampling the script with a curriculum that upweights rare words and domain terms early and ramps toward natural frequency later.\n\n3) Pretrain the ASR encoder with a unified supervised plus self-supervised objective. Use a wav2vec 2.0–style stack with a quantizer and transformer context network. Jointly optimize (i) CTC on high-resource labeled speech and on a quality-controlled subset of the synthetic speech-text pairs to encourage phone-aligned features, and (ii) masked contrastive learning on large amounts of unlabeled target audio mixed with the remaining synthetic audio to adapt the codebook and contextual space to the target acoustics and vocabulary. After convergence, freeze the feature encoder or apply a low learning rate to stabilize downstream tuning.\n\n4) Fine-tune with minimal real labels, strong pseudo-labels, and a calibrated curriculum. Use a strong multilingual teacher ASR to transcribe the unlabeled target audio; keep only high-confidence segments and filter with the domain lexicon and LM to reduce homophone and OOV errors. Train the student on a mixture of the small real labeled set, high-confidence pseudo-labels, and a downweighted sample of synthetic pairs. Start with real+pseudo data, anneal synthetic weight as WER drops, and gradually admit lower-confidence pseudo-labels if the dev set improves. Use CTC or RNN-T loss with SpecAugment and speed perturbation; add parameter-efficient adapters or selectively unfreeze upper transformer layers for domain adaptation. Decode with beam search and shallow-fuse the domain LM; optionally rescore with the transformer LM. Iterate: re-transcribe unlabeled audio with the improved student, refresh the LM on new transcripts, and regenerate a small tranche of harder synthetic utterances focused on remaining error modes until dev WER plateaus.",
  "rationale": "Domain-matched text determines the vocabulary and n-gram statistics that drive ASR decoding; retrieving and transforming existing datasets yields high-coverage scripts without costly manual authoring. High-fidelity multilingual TTS, trained via transfer, can then turn these scripts into acoustically diverse, label-perfect pairs that inject the right terms, numbers, and entities into the acoustic model and LM, even when human transcripts are scarce.\n\nUnified supervised plus self-supervised pretraining aligns the encoder to phonetic structure while adapting its latent space to target acoustics using abundant unlabeled audio. This produces features that transfer with little labeled data. Finally, confidence-filtered pseudo-labeling exploits all available target audio to close the domain gap, while curriculum weighting and parameter-efficient adaptation prevent overfitting to synthetic artifacts. Shallow-fusion with the domain LM ensures the decoder respects target phrasing and terminology, pushing accuracy toward competitive levels with only a small real labeled set.",
