  "method": "We propose RAPSODY, a low-label ASR training recipe that pairs a structure-aware encoder with two nonstandard supervision signals and a look-ahead synthetic curriculum. First, we insert a Global Temporal Prior Attention (GTPA) module into a mid layer of a Conformer/Transformer encoder. GTPA learns a small bank of reusable attention templates over time that encode language- and domain-agnostic temporal relations (e.g., local context, syllable-scale spans, onset–nucleus–coda and long-range vowel/consonant dependencies). For each frame t, we crop an aligned h×h sub-map from each global template, normalize it into token-to-token weights, apply it to values, and mix the result with multi-head self-attention via learned gates. This adds few parameters, regularizes attention toward speech-appropriate structures, and reduces overfitting in low-resource transfer.\n\nSecond, we replace standard pseudo-label pretraining with Rendition-Stack Consistency. For each text segment, we form a stack of heterogeneous audio renditions: diverse multi-speaker TTS, speed/pitch/noise perturbations, and optional voice-converted in-domain utterances aligned to that text. We enforce a denoising consistency objective that pulls encoder and decoder hidden states for all items in a stack toward a shared text-conditioned prototype (computed as the moving-average feature of a random pair in the stack), using a cosine similarity loss at multiple layers. The supervised head (CTC or transducer) is trained on the small real labeled set only; stacks do not require frame-level alignments. This consolidates speaker, channel, and prosody variation while keeping content fixed, yielding invariant features that transfer across accents and domains with minimal labels.\n\nThird, we introduce Listwise Hypothesis Distillation without ground truth to exploit unlabeled in-domain audio. The current ASR produces n-best hypotheses per utterance. A composite scorer (domain LM, pronunciation/lexicon prior, and an LLM judge scoring semantic plausibility for the target domain) induces a strict ranking over the n-best. We optimize the acoustic model and fusion weights with a differentiable listwise loss (e.g., weighted RankNet/Plackett–Luce) so that the model’s scores respect the external ranking. To avoid hurting partially correct hypotheses, we filter “negatives” with an LLM that flags hypotheses containing correct substrings/entities as ambiguous rather than incorrect; only truly irrelevant hypotheses contribute as negatives. This converts readily-available priors into powerful, label-free supervision that goes beyond top-1 pseudo-labels.\n\nFinally, we drive synthetic data generation with Look-ahead Curriculum Planning. We define coverage goals (“skills”) over phoneme n-grams, tones/prosody patterns, morphology, and domain entity pronunciation variants. Simple regressors estimate the expected WER improvement from adding a candidate synthetic batch given the model’s current confusion profile and the batch’s coverage statistics. A short-horizon tree search samples generation actions (speaker/pace/noise profiles, lexicon variants, entity lists), prunes low-value branches via success predictors, and chooses the next synthetic batch to materialize from TTS/VC. We alternate planning–generation–training rounds, annealing the synthetic mix as the model’s uncertainty shrinks. Throughout, GTPA parameters are shared across languages and updated jointly, enabling cross-lingual transfer of temporal priors even when labeled target data is scarce.\n\nTraining schedule: warm-start the encoder on any public speech with masked prediction only to stabilize features; insert GTPA and fine-tune briefly on the small labeled set to set the supervised head; then alternate (a) Rendition-Stack Consistency on synthetic stacks, (b) Listwise Hypothesis Distillation on unlabeled in-domain audio, and (c) Look-ahead Curriculum Planning to choose the next synthetic tranche. Decode with a light domain LM (or shallow fusion) during the listwise phase; remove or down-weight it at the end if end-to-end decoding is desired. This end-to-end process reaches competitive accuracy with minimal real labels by combining structure priors, label-free listwise supervision, and planned synthetic coverage.",
  "rationale": "GTPA injects reusable, speech-appropriate attention structure into the encoder, improving generalization when labeled target data is limited and reducing the burden on data to teach long- and mid-range temporal dependencies. Rendition-Stack Consistency exploits abundant synthetic variation anchored to identical text to explicitly disentangle content from nuisance factors, providing stronger invariance than standard augmentation alone while consuming no additional labels. Listwise Hypothesis Distillation turns readily available external knowledge (domain LM, lexicon, LLM semantic judgments) into a dense supervision signal on unlabeled audio, leveraging the full n-best list rather than brittle top-1 pseudo-labels and guarding against false-negative penalties.\n\nThe look-ahead synthetic curriculum addresses the core inefficiency of naive TTS augmentation: not all synthetic utterances are equally useful. By planning over phonetic/prosodic/entity coverage with simple, learned improvement predictors, the system preferentially generates batches that close the model’s current weaknesses, yielding faster gains under a fixed synthetic budget. These mechanisms are complementary: structure priors ease transfer, stack consistency builds robust representations, listwise distillation aligns scoring to domain semantics without labels, and planning ensures synthetic data is targeted, together enabling competitive ASR with minimal real supervision.",
