  "method": "Start from a strong self-supervised ASR backbone (e.g., a multilingual wav2vec-style encoder with a CTC/Transducer head) and keep it largely frozen. Insert lightweight, domain- and language-specific adapters in several transformer blocks, and add a single global, learnable acoustic prompt in the front end (a small time–frequency convolutional residual that perturbs inputs). Train only the adapters, the prompt, and the final prediction head on a few hours of real transcribed audio to anchor the mapping for the target language/domain. Maintain a small held-out dev set for thresholding and early stopping.\n\nCreate abundant paired data by synthesizing speech from large in-domain text. Use multi-speaker TTS when available; otherwise rely on cross-lingual TTS/voice conversion or a phoneme-based TTS seeded by grapheme-to-phoneme rules shared with related languages. Match target acoustics via augmentation and style transfer (reverberation, noise, channel, speaking rate, accent perturbations). Jointly train with two auxiliary objectives that do not need transcripts: masked acoustic modeling on unlabeled audio to stabilize the frozen backbone’s features, and a mix-and-separate branch trained on synthetic source mixtures to learn to suppress interferers and noise. Train or adapt a small domain language model on the same text for shallow fusion at decode time.\n\nLeverage unlabeled in-domain audio with teacher-guided self-training. Generate pseudo-transcripts using a strong external teacher ASR and score each utterance and token for confidence. Equip the student with a cheap deterministic uncertainty head that reads pre-logit representations and outputs per-utterance confidence; filter or down-weight pseudo-labels using the minimum of teacher and student confidence. Aggregate data iteratively in a DAgger-like loop: each round, add high-confidence pseudo-labeled segments and a budget of disagreement-focused segments where the teacher is confident but the student errs, so learning targets the student’s blind spots. Balance batches across gold, synthetic, and pseudo data, gradually shifting weight toward confident in-domain pseudo data as training progresses.\n\nReduce domain mismatch with feature-level adversarial alignment between target-domain unlabeled audio and the synthetic/limited labeled pool, applied on the shared encoder features while keeping the backbone frozen. For low-confidence segments, replace hard labels with consistency regularization: enforce prediction stability under strong acoustic augmentations rather than trusting noisy text. Update the global acoustic prompt with an uncertainty-guided EMA so it adapts more on hard, uncertain samples and stabilizes on easy ones. To prevent confirmation bias, keep the external teacher fixed (or use a slow EMA teacher distinct from the student), gate all threshold updates on the held-out dev set, and stop self-training rounds when dev WER plateaus.\n\nAt inference, enable the learned acoustic prompt and target adapters, decode with beam search and shallow-fused domain LM, and optionally run the separation-enhancement branch for noisy inputs. This configuration preserves the pretrained model’s generalization, adds only small domain-specific parameters, and exploits synthetic text and unlabeled audio to approach competitive accuracy with minimal real transcripts.",
  "rationale": "The backbone contributes powerful acoustic-linguistic representations; adapting only small adapters and a global acoustic prompt exploits that capacity with few labeled examples, reflecting evidence that much task ability is already present in pretrained networks. Synthetic TTS pairs inject large, domain-relevant supervision while auxiliary masked modeling and mix-and-separate training improve robustness to noise and overlapping speech without extra labels. A teacher-driven, confidence-weighted self-training loop converts unlabeled audio into useful supervision and focuses learning where the student most needs it, while deterministic uncertainty filtering and dev-set gating curb self-training bias. Adversarial alignment and uncertainty-guided prompt updates further close the domain gap with minimal additional parameters.\n\nTogether, these pieces turn abundant unlabeled audio and text into effective training signals, keep the finetuning footprint small, and mitigate the failure modes of naive pseudo-labeling. The result is a practical path to competitive ASR accuracy in low-resource languages or specialized domains using only a few hours of real transcriptions.",
